isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.48) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.16. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.26, p < .001, 95% CI [13.02, 14.04]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.37, p = 0.726, 95% CI [-0.85, 0.59]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.22, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.65, S.E. = 0.63, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.89, -1.42]; Std. beta = -0.69, 95% CI [-1.01, -0.37])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.71, S.E. = 0.86, p = 0.002, 95% CI [-4.41, -1.02]; Std. beta = -0.70, 95% CI [-1.15, -0.26])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
